{
  "text": "In a sense, Theorem 1 reflects our intuition that slabs are too clumsy a set of generators to construct interesting arrays. An immediate corollary of Theorem 1 is that the only indecomposable P p 1 ,...,p k -tilings are translates of p 1 Z, . . . , p k Z. One can apply the same argument to show that the only indecomposable P n 1 ,...,n k -tilings are the translates of n 1 Z, . . . , n k Z when the n i 's are pairwise coprime (this is a special case of one of the main results of [CITATION_1] ). We now take a look at the structure of the ideal generated by T 1 (X),. . . , T k (x) when the n i 's have many prime factors in common. For concreteness, say that Call a fiber any array consisting of a single line of 1's running parallel to one of the coordinate axes and running the full length of the array. By the above remarks, a polynomial of the form x j T i (x) mod 1 − x M maps to a fiber running parallel to the i-th coordinate axis. Thus elements of the ideal generated by",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "15075232"
